33
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
Furgle had been addicted to alcohol before he arrived in Rwanda, but now he had another addiction to cope with.

34
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:39,000
The need to keep returning to war. Furgle knew it wasn't healthy, but he couldn't stop.

35
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Around the year 2001, it seemed that war was everywhere, and Furgle kept on reporting.

36
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:51,000
In Sudan, Iraq, Afghanistan and Lebanon.

37
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
But the nightmares didn't stop, and his mental health got worse and worse.

38
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:02,000
Here Furgle takes up the story with BBC World Service Programme, lives less ordinary.

39
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
A reach a point where I can't carry that anymore.

40
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:10,000
And it's not dramatic, it's a slow, steady erosion.

41
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And that ends with a breakdown and admission to hospital.

